body:
Could you clarify a little what do you think should be done in this issue? Does a change like this:

```
public class Assertions {
    public static AbstractBigDecimalAssert<?> assertThat(BigDecimal actual) {
        return new BigDecimalAssert(actual);
}
```

is all that is needed? And I'm not sure what does 'In this case he will be able to extend Assertions class and hide its method like this' mean.

For example, I would like to extend BigDecimalAssert. 

For this, I need to create subclass of AbstractBigDecimalAssert and add there some custom assertion methods. Let's name this custom assert as MyBigDecimalAssert.

Then I need to register this newly created MyBigDecimalAssert in my own Assertions subclass (as described [here](http://joel-costigliola.github.io/assertj/assertj-core-custom-assertions.html) :

``` java
MyAssertions extends Assertions {
  public static MyBigDecimalAssert  assertThat(BigDecimal actual) {
    return new  MyBigDecimalAssert(actual);
  } 
}
```

But I can't do it right now, because Assertions class already contains assertThat(BigDecimal) method.
But it will be possible if this method return type is AbstractBigDecimalAssert instead of BigDecimalAssert.

Integrating this change has some positive and not so positive side effects.

It would be possible indeed to extend any exisiting Assert class and still have assertion chaining correct but this require non trivial generic definition.

I have taken @dmitry-treskunov example to add a `BigDecimal` assertion : 

``` java
public class MyAbstractBigDecimalAssert<S extends MyAbstractBigDecimalAssert<S>> 
             extends AbstractBigDecimalAssert<S> {

  protected MyAbstractBigDecimalAssert(BigDecimal actual, Class<S> selfType) {
    super(actual, selfType);
  }

  public S isOne() {
    if (actual != null && actual.compareTo(BigDecimal.ONE) != 0) {
      failWithMessage("Expected BigDecimal to be one but was <%s>", actual);
    }
    return myself;
  }
}
```

I also added a non generic class to avoid warning in `MyProjectAssertions` entry point class:

``` java
public class MyBigDecimalAssert extends MyAbstractBigDecimalAssert<MyBigDecimalAssert> {

  protected MyBigDecimalAssert(BigDecimal actual) {
    super(actual, MyBigDecimalAssert.class);
  }
}
```

`MyProjectAssertions` extends the regular `Assertions` class : 

``` java
public class MyProjectAssertions extends Assertions {  
  public static MyBigDecimalAssert assertThat(BigDecimal actual) {
    return new MyBigDecimalAssert(actual);
  }  
}
```

Ok, now I can write: 

``` java
assertThat(BigDecimal.ONE).isNotZero().isOne();
```

Note that we start with a regular `BigDecimal` assertion from `AbstractBigDecimalAssert` and yet we can chain with the one from `MyAbstractBigDecimalAssert`, this is because 
`assertThat(BigDecimal.ONE)` has returned `AbstractBigDecimalAssert` and not `BigDecimalAssert`.

Still with me ?  Now the not so good side effects, best explained with a String assertion example:

Since `assertThat("Yoda")` returns `AbstractCharSequenceAssert`, if we want to use `Condition`, we have to create a `Condition<AbstractCharSequenceAssert>`.
Same thing apply with `usingComparator`, in the following code 

``` java
assertThat("Frodo").usingComparator(caseInsensitiveStringComparator).startsWith("fr").endsWith("ODO");
```

`caseInsensitiveStringComparator` is a `Comparator<CharSequence>`, not a `Comparator<String>`.

_Conclusion open to discussion:_

Although it works this is not super obvious for the end user ... I'm wondering if this addition is really worth it.

@joel-costigliola both of your doubts are solved with one change. In `Assertions`, instead of 

```
public static AbstractCharSequenceAssert<?, ?> assertThat(String actual) {
    return new StringAssert(actual);
}
```

, change it to

```
public static AbstractCharSequenceAssert<?, String> assertThat(String actual) {
    return new StringAssert(actual);
}
```

Then the examples you cited work the same as before.
